Program 3: Function Overloading
Aim: To illustrate the concept of function overloading in C++.

Algorithm:

Start the program.
Define a class MathOperation.
Overload the function add() with different parameter lists.
Call the overloaded functions.
Stop the program.
Source Code:

#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

class MathOperation {
public:
    int add(int a, int b) { return a + b; }
    float add(float a, float b) { return a + b; }
    int add(int a, int b, int c) { return a + b + c; }
};

int main() {
    MathOperation m;
    cout << "Sum of two integers: " << m.add(10, 20) << endl;
    cout << "Sum of two floats: " << m.add(5.5f, 4.5f) << endl;
    cout << "Sum of three integers: " << m.add(1, 2, 3) << endl;
    return 0;
}
Result:

Sum of two integers: 30
Sum of two floats: 10
Sum of three integers: 6
